With a similar but less extreme result.

My first thought was that sorting brings the data into the cache, but that's silly because the array was just generated.

What is going on?
Why is processing a sorted array faster than processing an unsorted array?

answer:
It turns out that there weren't any cache-related optimizations to be gained here, but the code was almost as fast as a micro-benchmark suggested it would be.

The reason is that the primary loop is very fast:

for (int i = 0; i < 100000; ++i)
{   // Primary loop.
    for (int c = 0; c < arraySize; ++c)
    {   // Primary loop.
        if (data[c] >= 128)
            sum += data[c];
    }
}

This is because it's doing nothing but a single addition of an int, so it's essentially an instruction cache hit.

The primary loop is fast for a few reasons.

1: Integer add is fast. It's one of the fastest operations on a CPU.

2: Integers are always stored in a register. They never have to be loaded from memory or written to memory.

3: The primary loop only contains a single integer addition. The CPU can do this operation very quickly.

